    <definition xml:id="defn-absolute-extrema">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a function <m>f</m>,
          we say that <m>f(c)</m> is a <term>global</term> or
          <term>absolute maximum</term>
              <idx><h>maximum</h><h>global</h></idx>
              <idx><h>maximum</h><h>absolute</h></idx>
          of <m>f</m> provided that
          <m>f(c) \ge f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>,
          and similarly we call <m>f(c)</m> a <term>global</term>
              <idx><h>minimum</h><h>global</h></idx>
          or
          <term>absolute minimum</term>
              <idx><h>minimum</h><h>absolute</h></idx>
          of <m>f</m> whenever <m>f(c) \le f(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>


    <activity xml:id="activity-ad-extrema-1">
<statement>
    <P>According to <xref ref="defn-absolute-extrema"/>, which of the following statements best describes the absolute extrema (maximum and minimum) of the function in <xref ref="height-function"/>?</P>
    <ol label="A">
                <li><p> The absolute maximum is <m>x = 1</m>, because this is where the function has its maximum value. </p></li>
                <li><p> The absolute maximum is <m>s(1) = 64</m>, because this is the maximum value of the function.</p></li>
                <li><p> The graph has two absolute minima at the endpoints.</p></li>
                <li><p> The graph has one absolute minimum. </p></li>
            </ol>
    </statement>
</activity>

<p>
    From <xref ref="activity-ad-extrema-1"/> we notice that there are some issues when determining the absolute mimimum and maximum values of a function from its graph alone.  This leads us to the following Extreme Value Theorem.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id = "thm-extreme-value-theorem">
        <statement>
            <p>If <m>f</m> is continuous on a closed interval <m>[a,b]</m>, then <m>f</m> has both an absolute maximum and an absolute minimum on the interval.</p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>


